{
    "id": "electronics/arduino-blink",
    "title": "Blink an LED with Arduino",
    "description": "Learn to program a microcontroller by blinking an LED.",
    "image": "/assets/quests/basic_circuit.svg",
    "npc": "/assets/npc/orion.jpg",
    "start": "start",
    "dialogue": [
        {
            "id": "start",
            "text": "Hey there! Orion here. Ready to blink an LED with a microcontroller? Work on a dry, non-conductive surface, put on safety goggles if you have them and keep power disconnected until every wire is verified.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "materials",
                    "text": "Absolutely! What do I need?"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "materials",
            "text": "Gather an Arduino Uno, breadboard, two male-to-male jumper wires, a 220 Ω resistor, a 5 mm LED, a USB Type-A to USB-B cable and a laptop with the Arduino IDE installed. Follow the 'Install the Arduino IDE' process if needed. Verify the resistor's red-red-brown bands and that the LED's longer leg is the anode. With the board unplugged, route the anode to pin 13 through the resistor and connect the cathode to GND.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "arduino-ide-install",
                    "text": "Install the Arduino IDE"
                },
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "upload",
                    "text": "Got it all wired up. What's next?",
                    "requiresItems": [
                        {
                            "id": "72b4448e-27d9-4746-bd3a-967ff13f501b",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "d1105b87-8185-4a30-ba55-406384be169f",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "3cd82744-d2aa-414e-9f03-80024b624066",
                            "count": 2
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "48cf736e-184c-4bd1-b9b0-15b7e9721646",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "037e6065-68a7-4ad1-9b0b-7778ecfe0662",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "fb60696a-6c94-4e5e-9277-b62377ee6d73",
                            "count": 1
                        },
                        {
                            "id": "b6fc1ed6-f399-4fdb-9f9d-3913f893f43d",
                            "count": 1
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "upload",
            "text": "Connect the board to the laptop using the USB cable. Open the Arduino IDE and load File > Examples > 01.Basics > Blink. In Tools set Board to Arduino Uno and Port to your device, then click Upload and wait for 'Done uploading'. The board resets and the LED blinks once per second. Keep fingers off the circuit while it's powered.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "goto",
                    "goto": "finish",
                    "text": "Upload complete and the LED is blinking!"
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "finish",
            "text": "Nice work—you just programmed a microcontroller. Always unplug the USB cable before adjusting wiring. For a detailed walkthrough, open the 'Blink an LED with Arduino' process. Try new patterns and sensors to build skills for bigger projects.",
            "options": [
                {
                    "type": "process",
                    "process": "arduino-led-blink",
                    "text": "Open the detailed blink process"
                },
                {
                    "type": "finish",
                    "text": "Thanks Orion, that was awesome!"
                }
            ]
        }
    ],
